Page 3: Proposal: Shared Library Decomposition and Ownership Model

Purpose

This proposal recommends restructuring the current shared library model to reduce coupling, improve maintainability, and limit cross-business impact from shared component changes.

The aim is to separate truly common technical functionality from exception handling and business-area-specific logic, and to establish clearer ownership of shared components.

Current Issue

The current shared library has evolved into a large multi-purpose component and now contains multiple responsibilities, including common utilities, exception handling, and business-area-specific code.

This increases operational and delivery risk unnecessarily. A change in the shared library can affect many applications, including those outside the intended business area.

As a result:
	•	change impact becomes harder to assess
	•	testing scope becomes wider than necessary
	•	release coordination becomes more difficult
	•	ownership is less clear
	•	business-specific logic is mixed with technical common code

Why This Matters

Changes have a wider impact than necessary

When too much logic sits in one shared library, even small changes can affect multiple applications and business areas.

Testing becomes broader and slower

Because many applications depend on the same shared component, more regression confidence is needed for each change.

Ownership and boundaries are unclear

When technical utilities, exception handling, and business-specific logic are all grouped together, it becomes harder to decide who owns what and where new code should be placed.

Proposed Change

Move toward a more modular shared library model.

In this model:
	•	truly common technical utilities remain in a central shared component
	•	exception handling is separated into its own component
	•	business-area-specific reusable code is moved into business-area-specific shared libraries
	•	ownership is defined for each shared component

This would reduce unnecessary dependency on a single large shared library.

Benefits
	•	reduced cross-business impact from shared library changes
	•	easier impact analysis
	•	safer and more targeted testing
	•	clearer ownership of shared components
	•	better separation between technical common code and business-specific code
	•	improved long-term maintainability

Challenges
	•	refactoring effort will be required
	•	current library usage and dependencies need to be understood
	•	migration will need to be phased
	•	versioning and ownership standards will need to be defined

What Would Need to Change
	•	shared library structure
	•	dependency management
	•	ownership model
	•	coding standards for what qualifies as common
	•	migration plan for existing consumers

Recommendation

It is recommended that the current shared library be reviewed and gradually decomposed into smaller components with clearer responsibility boundaries.

The initial focus should be on separating exception handling from the main shared library and identifying business-area-specific code that should move into domain-specific shared components.

This change should be treated as a maintainability, testability, and risk-reduction improvement.

